Always trying to find the best way to do everything. In the end its worth it though, I get what she means. I feel exactly the same. It's just about like if you get to absorbed in it. You just can't let it go to far, otherwise you loose your mind in anxiety. The only reason you would ever need exposure therapy or cbt etc for this, is if it was interfering with your life and what you care about / doing things. But for her, it's fine. Shes not paralyzed by it. I'm alg now though. It took me years though. Often when things are stressful in your life you seek to feel safe and in control of something. It's not the worse coping mechanism but it can distract you from the issue.
ITS ALL ABOUT DETAILS. organizing is normal! needing things in order is fine! but its just when it goes detailed. when you start focusing on the irreverent and it interferes.

snippet.textDisplay: OCD has very little to do with being clean, there is no logic to someone with a compulsive disorder. It’s all linked to anxiety and no matter how much something is in order your brain tells you otherwise. Having ocd should not be confused with being a perfectionist. If you are a perfectionist, you want things to look perfect. However, ocd is about control and anxiety that’s why people with ocd perform rituals which are often associated to a number. Eg cleaning a particular area with a particular motion for a number of times even though the area is spotless and not carrying out this ritual can cause the person with that particular ocd distress and anxiety. Ocd is also not just about things being clean. It could be about how you turn of the lights or lock the door.
